<br>
Well hopefully I, as Donnalinna's avitar in the Real World, have peaked your interest enough in Donnalinna to try to figure  her out.  Well... this essay isn't really about Donnalinna; it's more an effort to give some thoughts and tips on role-playing, and how I came about with the idea of Donnalinna.  As well as some relation of these aspects to role-playing.  Do forgive, as with many of my essay's, I have a very indirect way of getting from point a to point b.  And, this might be kinda longish too.<br>
<br>
Well, if you didn't know already, I'm a guy.  Yes, a guy plays girly Donnalinna.  Now, for all you ladies out there (and it's eiree... I seem to know more female EQers than guys... but anyway), if I might ask a question, is Donnalinna a girl to you?  It makes me really giddy when people complement me on how  much of a personality and how 3-D Donnalinna is... and it's even more giddy when a girl or lady originally thought that Donnalinna's avitar was a girl too.  It makes me feel all this effort I put into it was worth it.<br>
<br>
Now, why do I bring this up?  Well, lets get a little background on me first.  Overall... in most of the computer RPGs, and other gaming stuff (pics in rule-books, collectable card-art, movies, bishoujo anime, etc.) to me the girl characters just look cooler.  The costumes, coreography, designs, etc really impressed me.  For example, in the recent movie Atlantis (which is about a 6 on a 1 - 10), the femme fatal Helga I thought was so keen.  Didn't really have much of a personality or character, but I really liked the way she was drawn.  Same goes for the Amazon and Sorceress in Diablo II.  I thought they're character models were tons cooler than the Necromancer and the Paladin's.  Now, this isn't to say that some of the guy characters don't look cool, or have a costuming that I really like (for example, I really liked how Gordon looked in Halflife, and the Beast-Form-Wizard in Gauntlet Legands is really keen); just, overall, I tend to like the way the girls are drawn.  So, extrapolate this to EQ, and you get me picking a female High Elf, because I thought she looked much better rendered.<br>
<br>
Okay now point two, I'm sure other guys play girl characters... but, unfortunatley, it's been my experience that most guys playing girls tend to play the girl as a &quot;sex-pot&quot;... i.e., perfect figure, and just out to see... how many... adult encounters she can have.  So... most women get offended by these characters.  Or, if not offended, at least disappointed.  Seriously, you've seen comic book heroines.  I think they all have the super power to fit those ridiculus figures into those super-tight, spandex costumes.   Anyway, I decided that dammit, I want to play a girl who's a girl.  So... I started thinking about what makes a girl a girl.<br>
<br>
However, I quickly came across a problem.  I'm a boy.  So... where do I get the inspiration on what a girl is like?  And it came to me, from my books.  I have a ton of literature that I own, as well as a ton of shoujo (girl's) anime, to drawn ideas from.  (And other books/stories are excellent places to get ideas on your own charcters personality from.)<br>
<br>
Most of my literature is split about 50-50 between guys stories and girl stories.  So... I started to piece together ideas of how girls act, what they like to do, and how &quot;femininity&quot; works.  Or... at least I tried my best to do so (and I hope that it's been working so far.)  So... Donnalinna likes to do girly things like sew and get dressed up and dance, she gets very flattered when gentlemen callers complement her, although she doesn't fight often, when she does, Hell hath no fury like Donnalinna.  So, hopefully, I made Donnalinna a real girl to you all.<br>
<br>
Now, that gave me some ground level stuff... but not Donnalinna.  So, next I decided that I would have one characterizing event that influances the rest of Donnalinna's upbringing.  Some of you may know it... others most likely not.  You might have ideas, but... overall I think you'd be surprized when you find out what happened in Donnalinna's past.<br>
<br>
Now, if you're curious, which you should be, why do you think Donnalinna is the way she is?  Well... lets look at what info is available right now.<br>
<br>
1) She's an High Elven Crown Princess (with all the pros and con's associated with it; i.e. she's proud, haughty, vainglorious, arrogant, compassionate, tender, merciful, used to getting her way, motherly to her subjects, hot/cold, etc., etc., etc.,  She's a fay princess, duh!  ^_^.)<br>
<br>
2) She's away from home with... dubious permission to have done so.  (She sometimes mentions Felwithe, but only to ask how the city has been... she rarely talks about going home.)<br>
<br>
3) She's a cleric of Tunare (now, couple this with her birth and upbringing, and she sometimes chafes at being a Servant of All.)<br>
<br>
4) She has a brother and a mother.  (If you ever really listen to her, she doesn't mention her father... much.)  Now she loves both her brother and mother... but her eyes do become sad, and her words guarded when she starts talking about them.<br>
<br>
5) She is depressed about something... but hasn't said what to the Congress of the Guild.  (She has hinted at it, but remember, she's of noble blood, and therefore finds it hard to talk about herself in a personal way... especially something so personal to people who she feels aren't her social-rank equals.)<br>
<br>
6) She talks about herself in the third person alot.  (now, possibly surprizing, this is a very important thing... take notice when Donnalinna refeers to herself as &quot;I&quot; or &quot;me&quot;... something very important to her is going on.)<br>
<br>
7) She is very formal when she receives a complement.  In fact... she asks you to stop doing so.  Now... why would someone who is as vain, vain to the point of being vain-glorious, as Donnalinna is ask you to stop complementing her?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  She gets jellous easily... but watch what she gets jellous over.  Perhaps... perhaps it isn't as obvious as it may seem.  (Remember Donnalinna cried at the RA 1 year anniversary because she wasn't part of anyone's stories.  Now, this might be because she's vain, and felt slighted that no one would tell a ballad of her... or perhaps she's... lonely, and was hoping that someone would tell a story of her, so she would feel more welcome.)<br>
<br>
9) She doesn't take the ribbing and joking at her expense well.  Now, this might be because she's a Crown Princess, and used to having no one say ill of her... or maybe it's because of something else why she doesn't like to be teased or made fun of.<br>
<br>
Now, you have some clues.   But... as with any good novel, you don't have a clear picture yet.  However, you should have enough that, if your familiar with how stories are told, you could give some very good guessess as to what happened.<br>
<br>
Curious yet ^_-?<br>
<br>
Anyway, I hope that helps you understand how I came about with Donnalinna's character, and perhaps curious enough to try to figure out, or directly ask, what happened in Donnalinna's past.  And, to give you ideas on how to give your own characters personalities.  The jist of it, there are a ton of stories out there that we've all read.  Who is to say you couldn't take Don Quixote's goofy-charm, mix in a bit of Sir Lancelot's prestigue and honor, add a dash of Will Scarlet's rougeish ways, and give that as a foundation for a personality.  That's about it.<br>
